column52: Provision of Integrated Community Musculoskeletal and Pain Management Service (IMSK) for NHS Milton Keynes Clinical Commissioning Group
column53:
NHS Milton Keynes Clinical Commissioning Group is planning to commence procurement for an Integrated Community Musculoskeletal and Pain Management Services (IMSK) in Milton Keynes. The contract is expected to be for up to 5 years (3 years initial term, with a 2 year option to extend) and to commence April 2017. The likely annual contract value is up to £550,000.

The aim of NHS Milton Keynes CCG for its musculoskeletal system is to provide effective treatment with the best possible patient experience for the investment made. 

The objectives of the IMSK service are to:
Provide Outpatient clinics closer to home for the patients 
Reduce the congestion on the secondary care waiting lists by diverting patients who do not need to go to a secondary care outpatient clinic and therefore help MKCCG and providers to achieve the 18 week Referral to Treatment target (RTT) 
Produce a ‘one stop shop’ for patients wherever possible to reduce the pathway time. 
Reduce the cost of the Outpatient appointments versus Payment by Results (PbR), either by commissioning services at a lower overall cost; reduce significantly the number of follow ups, whilst maintaining or improving a high quality of patient experience.

Documentation can be accessed at: https://ardengemcsu.bravosolution.co.uk

Arden and Greater East Midlands Commissioning Support Unit (Arden & GEM CSU), on behalf of the NHS Milton Keynes Clinical Commissioning Group would like to notify all potential bidders about a ‘Market Engagement Event’ which is scheduled to take place on Wednesday 14th September 2016 at 10.00 am – 11.30 am. 

Venue: Boardroom 2 NHS Milton Keynes CCG, Sherwood Place, Sherwood Drive, Bletchley, MK3 6RT.

For further details or to confirm your attendance please email Stephen.Ivuerah@ardengemcsu.nhs.uk by no later than 12 noon on Monday 12th September 2016. Please confirm the name of your organisation and the name and role of any attendee.  Please note attendees are limited to 2 per organisation.

column52: MS001 Construction related and FM services market sounding
column53:
As part of a fundamental review of its Design, Construction and Facilities Management (DCFM) related support services Birmingham City Council is seeking engagement and input from the external marketplace regarding the future development and operation of these services.

The Council’s aspiration for this market consultation is as follows:

1)  to allow the City Council to gain a greater understanding of the wider market opportunities, key developments and trends in relation to DCFM  services 
2)  to allow the City Council to consider options for shaping the structure and scope of these services in a way that is appropriate to Council business needs and priorities over the medium to long-term
3)  to allow public and private sector businesses /partnerships to express their interest and offer ideas for the delivery of these services. 
4)  to get a better understanding of the commercial opportunities (e.g. growth, investment and profit sharing) associated with these services 

Background

The current arrangements for delivering professional construction-related services were first explored by the Council in 2009, with approval being given to develop a Wholly-Owned Company given in January 2011.  BCC’S Wholly owned company – Acivico (Design Construction and Facilities Management) Limited and Acivico Integrated Services Ltd (Building Cleaning, Catering, and Birmingham City Laboratories Services (Acivico Ltd) (“BCC’s WOC”) was created as the Council’s Wholly-owned Company for these (and potentially future) services and were given for the term of a 5-year contract the exclusive right to undertake services outlined in this questionnaire for the Council up to end March 2017.  
As a Wholly-Owned Teckal company, Acivico is contracted to the Council as contract administrator, managing agent and for some services, a direct deliverer. 
If you are interested in participating in this market sounding exercise, please register an interest on in-tend.  

The web address is https://in-tendhost.co.uk/birminghamcc.  

Registration and use of in-tend is free. All correspondence for this soft market exercise must be via the in-tend correspondence function. If you have any problems in accessing in-tend please email us at cps@birmingham.gov.uk  or call 0121 464 8000.


Interested parties will be able to download from the e-portal a market sounding questionnaire.  Responses to this questionnaire, together with subsequent discussions with respondents, will be used to make an informed decision and assist the Council in constructing the future delivery models for these services.     

Submission of completed questionnaires is by noon on 7th October 2016. 


Additional information: If you are interested in tendering please click on the following link to access Birmingham City Council’s tender Portal.

Delivery Notes

Birmingham

column52: Support for Direct Payment Users
column53:
The Royal Borough of Kingston upon Thames and Kingston Clinical Commissioning Group are seeking to commission Direct Payment Support Services.
The main aim is to ensure users of services have greater choice and control over how their support is provided, with the support being both personalised and flexible.  The key aims of this service are to promote the effectiveness of personal budget direct payments and to ensure that direct payment users in Kingston are able to use them to lead fulfilling lives as independently as possible.
Commissioning support in this way is part of Kingston’s Active and Supportive Communities strategy which aims to assist adults in the Royal Borough of Kingston upon Thames to build and maintain the resilience that enables them to stay happy, healthy, socially active and able to cope in adversity.

column52: GB-London: Tender for Digital Marketing Services to Increase Public Use of CQC Inspection Information
column53:
NOTE: This notice was updated on 23 September 2016 for the following reason: Tender deadline extended to 5:00pm on 14/10/2016The Care Quality Commission (CQC) is the independent regulator of health and adult social care services in England. We are responsible for monitoring and inspecting services to ensure they are providing care that is safe, effective, caring, responsive to people’s needs and well-led. 

CQC is seeking to procure digital marketing services, in order to drive greater awareness of CQC and use of our inspection information amongst key segments of our public audience. CQC will use digital marketing to reach segments of our market that research has shown most value CQC’s information and services, and use the internet (primarily search engines) as a primary route to search for information in order to support decisions about which health or adult social care service to use. These segments are:

•People choosing adult social care services
•Pregnant women thinking about birth options
•People considering cosmetic surgery

This activity will support delivery of CQC's public engagement strategy and through that the organisation’s corporate objectives. CQC’s wider strategy for 2016-2021 commits the organisation to improve how we work with the public and people who use services.  It also makes clear that raising awareness of CQCs role and purpose is central to all elements of our work with people who use services and the public more broadly.

Additional information: The contracting authority considers that this contract may be suitable for economic operators that are small or medium enterprises (SMEs). However, any selection of tenderers will be based solely on the criteria set out for the procurement.

column52: Kirklees Integrated Healthy Child Programme (KIHCP)
column53: Tenderers are invited to submit prices for the Service, as specified in the Service Specification which has an estimated value throughout its initial lifetime of five (5) years is fifty three million seven hundred and eight five thousand three hundred and ninety pounds sterling (£53,785,390.00) The intention is to use the KIHCP approach for the integration of a range of systems, interventions and services in order to improve outcomes for children, young people, their families and communities, with a focus on mental and emotional health and wellbeing. Our vision: Kirklees is a great place to grow up where every child and young person: is safe and loved, healthy and happy and free from harm, and has the chance to make the most of their talents, skills and qualities to fulfil their potential. What do we want to achieve We want to bring together organisations, people and services to develop a shared approach so that: every child has the best start in life all children, young people and adults maximise their capabilities and have control over their lives. The plan covers the whole spectrum of services for children and young people's mental health and wellbeing from health improvement and prevention work, to support and interventions for children and young people who have existing or emerging mental health problems, as well as transitions between services. To design and deliver more integrated child and family health services in Kirklees using the framework of the HCP to improve the outcomes for children, young people and their families. The services that are currently delivering elements of the HCP and CAMHS include: Health visiting and family nurse partnership (0-5 year old public health resource). School nursing (5-19 year old public health resource) Children and adolescent mental health service (CAMHS) tiers 2 and 3 Learning from the pilot Single Point of Access in the CAMHS Transformation Plan Children's weight management service Healthy vitamin scheme. Commissioners hope that any potential model will be innovative and demonstrate a robust, fully integrated delivery partnership approach. They are intending to encourage collaboration wherever possible.

column52: BNSSG —Patient Transport Services (PTS).
column53:
The provision of Patient Transport Services for NHS Bristol Clinical Commissioning Group, NHS North Somerset Clinical Commissioning Group, and NHS South Gloucestershire Clinical.

The Department of Health defines Non-emergency Patient Transport Service (NEPTS or PTS) activity as being the non-urgent, planned transportation of patients, with a medical need for transport, to and from premises providing NHS healthcare.  This encompasses a wide range of vehicle types and levels of care consistent with the patients’ medical needs. The overarching principle of PTS is that patients who are eligible for transport will receive safe, timely, comfortable and appropriate transport, without detriment to their medical condition.

The requirement for BNSSG is split into two lots:
• Lot 1: BNSSG Patient Transport Services (PTS)
• Lot 2: BNSSG Renal Patient Transport Services 

In accordance with Public Contracts Regulations 2015, 46 (6); the contracting authorities reserve the right to award contracts combining both lots to the same tenderer.

The commissioners are considering a number of ways that PTS can be delivered in the BNSSG area, and wish to have further discussions with bidders regarding the risks and benefits of these options.  

The options in consideration by the commissioners are attached to this advert as a supporting document.

The contract will be based on a 5 year period with the option to extend by a further 2 years. The annual contract value is in the region of £3,900,000 per annum for lot 1 and in the region of £750,000 per annum for lot 2.  Final awarded values may differ to those noted above in line with the options and potential variations outlined above. 

The contract start date(s) will be the 1st of April 2017 to 31st March 2022, with an option to extend by a further two years at the Commissioners discretion.

The Commissioner is following a form of Accelerated Competitive Procedure with Negotiation due to urgency outside of the Authority's control.

Bidders are invited to register for 1:1 clarification sessions taking place on the 12th of September 2016 through the In-Tend eTendering portal.

Further information and tender documentation can be obtained via the following link: 
https://in-tendhost.co.uk/scwcsu/aspx/Home

Additional information: To receive more information about this tender, including the tender documentation and any amendments and/or clarifications and to request any clarifications and/or to respond to this tender, you must register your interest into this tender on the following website: https://in-tendhost.co.uk/scwcsu/aspx/Home

Once you have successfully registered your expression of interest you will be issued with the tender document for completion before the deadline stated within the tender documentation.

column52: Design and Delivery of a Professional Teacher Support Programme in Algeria
column53:
The British Council in Algeria has a cooperation agreement with the Algerian Ministry of National Education which outlines a number of areas for collaboration around Algerian aspirations for reform of school education and has received FCO funding to deliver a pilot project until March 2017 which will begin to address those aspirations, entitled ‘Promoting prosperity and economic development in Algeria through school-based professional development for new teachers: a pilot programme’. 

The British Council is seeking a supplier to design and deliver a pilot teacher development programme that works with the existing inspectorate system to improve the pedagogical skills of newly qualified teachers (of primary, middle and secondary schools across a range of curriculum subject areas) in Algeria. The supplier will develop a draft continuous professional development (CPD) framework that focuses on developing improved pedagogical skills and design, and deliver and support an appropriate accompanying training programme for inspectors, who will then work with teachers. Given the short timeframe for this project, the supplier will start from a suitable existing CPD framework.

The supplier should be an educational organisation that can provide a team of experts who will be expected to work in close collaboration with the Algerian Ministry of National Education and the British Council to ensure appropriate consultation and co-creation at each stage of the project.

Additional information: To access the documents you should register at https://in-tendhost.co.uk/britishcouncil and express an interest for this project, you will then be able to download the project documents

column52: Provision of Mental Health Crisis House Services for the population of Leicester, Leicestershire and Rutland on Behalf of Leicestershire Partnership NHS Trust
column53:
Health and social care partners within Leicester, Leicestershire and Rutland have recognised the need to ensure that a range of services is available to support service users at a time of mental health crisis.  The aim is to offer a greater choice of service and also to enhance the availability and accessibility of such services.

Following a successful pilot of the model during 2015 and 2016, the commissioner is looking to award a five year contract for provision of the following service:

Crisis houses provide an innovative approach to care and support for people experiencing serious mental illness who may otherwise require admission to hospital.

Recent evidence from Sweeney et al (2014), found that, ‘therapeutic alliances, service user satisfaction and informal peer support were greater in crisis house environments than on acute wards’.

Crisis houses provide a safe and therapeutic environment for immediate crisis support, whilst remaining focused on on-going recovery, building support networks and preventing future crises.

column52: CON - Supply of Electricity and Gas - Dynamic Purchasing System
column53:
Supply of Electricity and Gas - Dynamic Purchasing System.  Bristol City Authority (BCC) is seeking to establish a DPS which is open nationally for the use of UK public sector bodies and non-profit making organisation(s), subject to an access agreement between BCC and Authorised Purchaser(s). BCC may use the DPS to tender for supply contracts for its own metered sites and Highway unmetered supply installations, to schools for which it is LEA, and to Clients for whom it offers energy services. There is no guarantee of any contracts being awarded from this DPS. The award criteria for Call For Competition tenders may be on the basis of price or price and quality at the Purchasing Authority's discretion.  Variant bids will not be accepted in any application to be admitted to the DPS. However, variant bids might be allowed in call for competition tenders, subject to requirements of the Purchasing Authority, for example, pricing for renewable and/or conventionally sourced electricity. To be eligible for a place on this proposed DPS applicants must hold an electricity supply licence issued by the Office of the Gas and Electricity Markets (Ofgem) for Categories (Lots) 1 HH Electricity, 2 NHH Electricity and 3 UMS Electricity and / or a gas supply licence issued by Ofgem for Category (Lot) 4 Gas.  To be appointed to any Category of the DPS, Applicants must demonstrate their eligibility with regards to invoicing and payment allocation. To be appointed to any or all Categories 1, 2 and 4 of the DPS applicants must demonstrate that they meet the requirements with regards to appointment of metering and data agents -refer to the tender documents for further details.
Applicants must commit to £10 Million (GBP) Employers Liability and £5 Million (GBP) Public Liability Insurance.

Additional information: Please go to ProContract Supplier Portal on website https://procontract.due-north.
If you have any problems with the portal, please do not hesitate to contact the ProContract team on 01670 597137 Monday to Friday 8.30 am to 17.30 pm or email support@due-north.com

column52: Annual Billing for Council Tax and National Non Domestic Rates, and Electoral Registration Print Services
column53:
The Isle of Wight Council is responsible for the collection of both Council Tax and National Non Domestic Rates for the Isle of Wight. In addition it is the Authority’s responsibility to administer Housing benefit and the Local Council Tax Support scheme. As part of its statutory duties in this area the Authority has a legal obligation to issue annual Council Tax and National Non Domestic Rates bills under the Local Government Finance Act1992, The Council Tax (Administration & Enforcement) Regulations & Non Domestic Rating (Collection &Enforcement (Local Lists) Regulations 1989. 1.5 The Authority’s requirements are therefore for the supplier to produce, envelope and dispatch (including postage) the relevant documentation in relation to the following:
(a) Annual billing for Council Tax, (b)Annual billing for National Non Domestic Rates, (c)Housing Benefit notifications, (d)Ad-Hoc Billing for Council Tax, (e)Local Council Tax Support notifications

Additional information: Tenderers can bid for one or both of the lots. It is the tenderers responsibility to ensure that they request the documents in ample time to ensure that they can be completed and returned, along with all supporting documentation called for, prior to the closing time and date. The Council reserves the right not to make any award and reserves the right to accept all or part of any tender.

column52: Devonshire Park – Catering Opportunity
column53:
Eastbourne Borough Council is undertaking a £45M renovation and development of its primary leisure and cultural asset at Devonshire Park and, as part of this, an exciting opportunity will arise to become the catering partner of a range of fixed outlets and events  

We are now seeking Expressions of Interest to be the catering partner for this unique opportunity.  Eastbourne is a premier destination which welcomes over 5m visitors each year, offering a wealth of attractions and appealing to a diverse audience. 

The Devonshire Park Centre is fundamental to the visitor experience with the multi-use site ensuring the facilities are used all year round. With over 600 theatre shows from top comedians to west end musicals frequently selling out to enthralled audiences. 
The complex attracts over 270,000 patrons each year and a further 15,000 conference delegates. Enviable banqueting space with capacity up to 800 means it’s the first choice for awards ceremonies, charity fundraisers and Christmas party nights. Over 8,000 people enjoyed fine dining and over 200 meetings and events were held within the complex.

The procurement of selecting the catering partner will be two staged.  The first stage, this Expression of Interest ('EOI') period, will run until 28th October 2016. All interested parties are invited to complete the short EOI form and submit the initial details requested by this date to the InTend portal.

column52: Research into disabled passengers’ awareness and perceptions of assistance
column53:
This work is being commissioned by ORR’s Competition and Consumer Policy Team. The Team develops and advises on ORR’s competition and consumer policy, and has an enforcement role in these areas. The Team is also responsible for approving policies and monitoring compliance under passenger-facing licence conditions. 
Access to public transport is for many a necessity of everyday life. As the regulator, we recognise the importance of the rail network being open to everyone regardless of disability. It is our role, via the operating licences, to oversee that the operators of trains and stations enable passengers with a disability to make their journeys easily and confidently, whether those journeys are made independently or with assistance. One of the objectives in our current business plan is therefore to continue to monitor and enforce the obligations operators are accountable for under the terms of their operating licences.
In this context, train and station operators are required by their operating licences to establish and comply with a disabled people’s protection policy (DPPP). A DPPP sets out, amongst other things, the arrangements that an operator will put in place to support disabled people using its services. ORR is responsible for approving and monitoring the implementation of these DPPPs. A key element of DPPPs concerns the requirement that ‘each licensed operator must participate in a reservation system for disabled passengers whose journey begins at any of the stations at which that operator’s trains are scheduled to stop’. That current system is called Passenger Assist. Operators are expected to provide assistance that has been booked through Passenger Assist, at any station during the hours that trains are scheduled to serve that station. As part of our monitoring work we want to increase our evidence base, ensure that obligations in this area are being met and ensure that passengers are satisfied with the service they receive. 
Before we commission work to investigate passengers’ experience of assistance, we would first like to understand disabled people’s awareness of the assistance available to them on the rail network more generally. Our aim is to understand the extent to which current levels of usage reflect genuine demand. Where actual or perceived barriers to access are identified, we wish to explore these to understand how they can be mitigated.

Additional information: This tender closes on 20/09/2016 at 17:00. All communication must be via our portal.

column52: ARFQ - The Provision of Securing Works under Section 29 of the Local Government (Misc. Provisions) Act 1982 and Stabilisation Works under Sections 77 or 78 of the Building Act 1984
column53:
Under Section 29 of the Local Government (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1982, the Authority is responsible for ensuring that buildings which become both ‘vacant and insecure’ are re-secured against entry. The owners of the buildings are initially requested to carry out the work themselves but if this does not happen then the Authority are authorised to make arrangements to carry out the necessary work themselves (via a contractor).
The costs for carrying out these works are met by the Authority who in turn will recover the costs from the owner.

In a similar way, under Sections 77 or 78 of the Building Act 1984, the Authority is also responsible for ensuring that any structurally unstable buildings (or structures) are made safe by way of either stabilization or demolition. Again the owners of the buildings (or structures) are encouraged to carry out the works themselves but if this does not happen then the Authority are authorised to make arrangements to carry out the necessary work themselves (via a contractor). 
Again, the costs for carrying out these works are met by the Authority who in turn will recover the costs from the owner.

column52: Railway Memorial Gardens - Maintenance
column53:
The memorial gardens were constructed by Network Rail to commemorate the victims of individual rail accidents/disasters and provide a special and poignant way to remember loved ones.

 The gardens are frequently visited by survivors of the incidents, relatives of the victims and in some cases open to the public. They are all located on Network Rail land spanning various routes and we have a commitment to maintain them. 
 The first garden was built in 2002 in Great Heck near Selby, following the positive response a decision was made to erect ones at Southall, Hatfield and Potters Bar. More recently we have been asked to take over the maintenance of the small memorial site at Porthmadog, Wales. 

 This Contract is for the provision of a maintenance service for the Railway Memorial Gardens to include supplying labour, equipment and the appropriate products to maintain the garden planting, seating, stonework/paving, fencing and safe access at the above sites. However Porthmadog, Wales will only require three maintenance visits per year.

column52: Agreement for a Virtual Learning Environment - Cloud Based
column53:
The University is seeking to renew its institutional online learning provision, with a view to identifying a solution which will be fully operational from August 2107.
The University seeks a solution which will enable the institution to provide exceptional opportunities for online learning.
The system should:
• provide and support a full suite of content management and online learning tools
• afford a high degree of flexibility to adapt to the changing and future needs of the University
• be optimised for a range of mobile devices
• offer an intuitive interface and workflows
• deliver a high level of availability
• be secure and resilient
• support seamless integrations with other University business systems and learning applications
• produce meaningful usage data and reports to support student learning and academic practice

LJMU are currently in the process of procuring an E Tendering portal , however at the moment we do not have the facility to provide a url for documents to be accessed. The relevant documentation should be requested electronically via email to k.l.Houghton@ljmu.ac.uk

column52: CONSTRUCTION OF EXTERNAL FILM LOT
column53:
The BBC is conducting a competitive procurement for a Principal Contractor to undertake the construction of an external film lot, in accordance with the Restricted Procedure.. The permanent front lot represents the Construction of the front lot will be located on the land adjacent to the main entrance within what is currently largely car parking provision.

Additional information: Please register your interest in this project by taking the following steps:

1 - Register your company on the BravoSolution e-Tendering portal (this is only required once): 
 1.1 - Go to https://bbc.bravosolution.co.uk. 
1.2 - Click the link on the login page to Register.
1.3 - Accept the terms and conditions and click ‘Continue'.
1.4 - Enter your correct business and user details.
1.5 - Note the username you chose and click ‘Save' when complete.
1.6 - You will shortly receive an email with your temporary password.

 2 - Express an Interest in the tender: 
 2.1 - Login to the portal with the username/password.
2.2 - Click the ‘PQQs / ITTs Open To All Suppliers' link. (These are Pre-Qualification Questionnaires or Invitations to Tender open to any registered supplier).
2.3 - Click on the relevant PQQ/ ITT to access the content.
2.4 - Click the ‘Express Interest' button at the top of the page. This will move the PQQ /ITT into your ‘My PQQs/ My ITTs' page. (This is a secure area reserved for your projects only.
2.5 - You can now access any attachments by clicking ‘Buyer Attachments' in the ‘PQQ/ ITT Details' box.

  3. Responding to the tender:
3.1 - Click ‘My Response' under ‘PQQ/ ITT Details', you can choose to ‘Create Response' or to ‘Decline to Respond' (please give a reason if declining).
3.2 - You can now use the ‘Messages' function to communicate with the buyer and seek any clarification.
3.3 - Note the deadline for completion, then follow the onscreen instructions to complete the PQQ/ ITT There may be a mixture of online and offline actions for you to perform (there is detailed online help available).
3.4 - You must then submit your reply using the ‘Submit Response' button at the top of the page. 
 
 If you require any further assistance please consult the online help, or contact the Bravo e-Tendering help desk.
